@page "/learn/pow"
@layout Consensus.Web.Components.Layout.MainLayout

<PageTitle>Proof of Work · Tutorials · Consensus Lab</PageTitle>

<TutorialPage Title="Proof of Work (PoW)"
              Lede="The original Bitcoin protocol — computers race to solve a math puzzle, and the winner gets to add the next block."
              Difficulty="Beginner"
              ReadTime="~10 min">

    <h2>The basic idea</h2>

    <p>
        Imagine you're playing a game with 1,000 other kids in a giant classroom. The teacher
        says: "I'm thinking of a number between 1 and 10 trillion. First person to guess it
        gets to write the next page in the class journal." Everyone starts guessing as fast as
        they can — flipping calculators, scribbling numbers, trying combination after
        combination. Eventually one kid shouts the right number. They get to write the page;
        the teacher checks their answer in one second; everyone moves on.
    </p>

    <p>
        That's Proof of Work in a nutshell. Computers (called <strong>miners</strong>) race to
        find a special number that, when combined with the latest list of transactions,
        produces a cryptographic hash starting with a certain number of zeros. The puzzle is
        easy to <em>verify</em> (anyone can check the answer in milliseconds) but very hard to
        <em>solve</em> (you have to try billions of guesses).
    </p>

    <div class="analogy">
        <strong>Analogy:</strong> It's like a giant sudoku puzzle that takes hours to solve but
        takes ten seconds to check. Whoever cracks the puzzle first earns the right to add the
        next page to the shared notebook — plus a reward of newly-minted coins.
    </div>

    <h2>How a round works, step by step</h2>

    <MermaidDiagram Caption="One round of Proof of Work mining.">
flowchart TD
    Start([New transactions arrive]) --> Pool[Each miner gathers them<br/>into a candidate block]
    Pool --> Guess{Miner guesses<br/>a 'nonce' number}
    Guess --> Hash[Computes hash of block + nonce]
    Hash --> Check{Does the hash start<br/>with N zeros?}
    Check -- No --> Guess
    Check -- Yes --> Broadcast[Miner broadcasts<br/>the winning block]
    Broadcast --> Verify[Other miners verify<br/>in a few milliseconds]
    Verify --> Accept[Block is added to the chain]
    Accept --> Reward[Winner earns a coin reward]
    Reward --> Start
    </MermaidDiagram>

    <h2>Watch a round play out</h2>

    <p>
        The animation below shows one PoW round in slow motion. Six miners stand around a
        sender (centre). When the sender announces new transactions, all six start hashing.
        One of them (highlighted gold) gets lucky and finds a valid nonce, then broadcasts
        the winning block to everyone else. Tap <strong>Play</strong> to watch it run, or use
        the step controls to walk through phase by phase.
    </p>

    <ConsensusAnimation Title="Proof of Work — one round, six miners"
                        Actors="@_powActors" Steps="@_powSteps" />

@code {
    private static readonly List<ConsensusAnimation.Actor> _powActors =
        AnimationLayouts.RingWithCentre(
            peripheralCount: 6,
            centreId: "user",
            centreLabel: "User",
            centreColor: "#34495e",
            centreIcon: "👛",
            peripheralIdPrefix: "m",
            peripheralLabelPrefix: "Miner",
            peripheralIcon: "⛏");

    private static readonly List<ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep> _powSteps = new()
    {
        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "1. New transactions arrive",
            Description: "A user broadcasts pending transactions to every miner in the network.",
            Messages: AnimationLayouts.Broadcast("user", new[] {"m1","m2","m3","m4","m5","m6"},
                color: "#1976d2", label: "tx").ToList()),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "2. Every miner starts hashing",
            Description: "Each miner packages the transactions into a candidate block and starts trying nonces, racing for a hash with enough leading zeros.",
            Messages: new List<ConsensusAnimation.Message>(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"m1","m2","m3","m4","m5","m6"}),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "3. Miner 3 finds the winning nonce!",
            Description: "After billions of guesses, one miner stumbles onto a nonce whose hash starts with enough zeros. They win this round.",
            Messages: new List<ConsensusAnimation.Message>(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"m3"}),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "4. Winner broadcasts the new block",
            Description: "Miner 3 sends the block — transactions + winning nonce + hash — to every other miner.",
            Messages: AnimationLayouts.Broadcast("m3", new[] {"m1","m2","m4","m5","m6","user"},
                color: "#388e3c", label: "block").ToList(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"m3"}),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "5. Everyone verifies and accepts",
            Description: "Each miner checks the hash in milliseconds. The block is added to the chain; Miner 3 earns the reward; everyone starts hashing the next block.",
            Messages: new List<ConsensusAnimation.Message>(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"m1","m2","m3","m4","m5","m6","user"}),
    };
}

    <p>
        The hash function is the key. PoW uses a function called <strong>SHA-256</strong>
        which acts like a number scrambler: feed it any input, get a 256-bit output that looks
        completely random. The only way to find an input whose output starts with, say,
        20 zeros is to try inputs one at a time until you get lucky.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this works</h2>

    <p>
        Three properties make Proof of Work secure:
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <strong>Costly to attack.</strong> If a bad actor wanted to rewrite history (say,
            replace the page where they paid Alice with a page where they paid themselves),
            they'd need to re-mine that block <em>plus every block after it</em>, all faster
            than the rest of the network combined. That requires owning more than half of the
            world's mining computers — wildly expensive.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Cheap to verify.</strong> Anyone can check a block in milliseconds. So even
            phones can keep the network honest.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Self-adjusting difficulty.</strong> If miners get faster collectively (because
            new hardware appears), the protocol automatically raises the number of leading zeros
            so the average time between blocks stays around 10 minutes (in Bitcoin's case).
        </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>The real-world picture</h2>

    <p>
        <strong>Bitcoin</strong>, the most famous use of PoW, has been running this way since 2009.
        Globally, the Bitcoin network performs <em>roughly half a quintillion</em> hash guesses
        per second — a number with 18 zeros. That's why people sometimes talk about Bitcoin
        using as much electricity as a small country. Other PoW chains include
        <strong>Litecoin</strong>, <strong>Dogecoin</strong>, and (until 2022)
        <strong>Ethereum</strong>.
    </p>

    <h2>Strengths and trade-offs</h2>

    <div class="pro-con-grid">
        <div class="pro-card">
            <h4>✅ Strengths</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Extremely battle-tested — Bitcoin has run uninterrupted since 2009</li>
                <li>No central authority can shut it down or veto a block</li>
                <li>Attacks are economically irrational at scale</li>
                <li>Anyone with a computer can join the network</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="con-card">
            <h4>⚠️ Trade-offs</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Enormous electricity consumption — environmental cost</li>
                <li>Slow: Bitcoin processes ~7 transactions per second</li>
                <li>Mining tends to centralize where electricity is cheapest</li>
                <li>Specialized hardware (ASICs) gives big players an edge</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>A bit of math: the puzzle, simplified</h2>

    <p>
        In our simulator, a PoW round looks like this. The miner takes the block's data and tries
        a "nonce" (a counter), computes the hash, and checks for leading zeros:
    </p>

    <pre style="background: var(--mud-palette-background-grey); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 6px; overflow-x: auto;"><code>nonce = 0
while True:
    candidate = block_data + str(nonce)
    h = sha256(candidate)
    if h.startswith("0000"):     # difficulty = 4 leading zeros
        return nonce, h          # found it — broadcast!
    nonce += 1                   # try the next number
</code></pre>

    <p>
        On a real Bitcoin miner the difficulty is much higher — closer to 19 or 20 leading zeros
        in hex — and the loop runs trillions of times per second on dedicated hardware.
    </p>

    <div class="try-it">
        <h3>🎮 Try it in the simulator</h3>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-2">
            Start a Proof of Work simulation with 10 nodes and watch the round-time tile fluctuate
            — that's the puzzle-finding luck in action. Use seed=42 to get reproducible numbers,
            then compare the leader distribution against the Gini-fairness metric.
        </MudText>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Filled" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.PlayCircle"
                   Href="/simulations">Run a PoW simulation</MudButton>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Text" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.QueryStats"
                   Href="/specialized-analytics">View PoW analytics</MudButton>
    </div>

